axiom="X"
rules=list("X"="F-[[X]+X]+F[+FX]-X", "F"="FF")
angle=22.5
depth=6


for (i in 1:depth) axiom=gsubfn(".", rules, axiom)

actions=str_extract_all(axiom, "\\d*\\+|\\d*\\-|F|L|R|\\[|\\]|\\|") %>% unlist

status=data.frame(x=numeric(0), y=numeric(0), alfa=numeric(0))
points=data.frame(x1 = 0, y1 = 0, x2 = NA, y2 = NA, alfa=90, depth=1)


# Generating data
# Note: may take a minute or two

for (action in actions)
{
  if (action=="F")
  {
    x=points[1, "x1"]+cos(points[1, "alfa"]*(pi/180))
    y=points[1, "y1"]+sin(points[1, "alfa"]*(pi/180))
    points[1,"x2"]=x
    points[1,"y2"]=y
    data.frame(x1 = x, y1 = y, x2 = NA, y2 = NA,
               alfa=points[1, "alfa"],
               depth=points[1,"depth"]) %>% rbind(points)->points
  }
  if (action %in% c("+", "-")){
    alfa=points[1, "alfa"]
    points[1, "alfa"]=eval(parse(text=paste0("alfa",action, angle)))
  }
  if(action=="["){
    data.frame(x=points[1, "x1"], y=points[1, "y1"], alfa=points[1, "alfa"]) %>%
      rbind(status) -> status
    points[1, "depth"]=points[1, "depth"]+1
  }

  if(action=="]"){
    depth=points[1, "depth"]
    points[-1,]->points
    data.frame(x1=status[1, "x"], y1=status[1, "y"], x2=NA, y2=NA,
               alfa=status[1, "alfa"],
               depth=depth-1) %>%
      rbind(points) -> points
    status[-1,]->status
  }
}

ggplot() +
  geom_segment(aes(x = x1, y = y1, xend = x2, yend = y2),
               lineend = "round",
               color="darkgreen", # Set your own Fall color?
               data=na.omit(points)) +
  coord_fixed(ratio = 1) +
  theme_void() # No grid nor axes

#  Examples of standard high-level plots 

### Setting the parameter (3 rows by 2 cols)
par(mfrow=c(3, 2))

## Scatterplot

x <- c(0.5, 2, 4, 8, 12, 16)
y1 <- c(1, 1.3, 1.9, 3.4, 3.9, 4.8)
y2 <- c(4, .8, .5, .45, .4, .3)

## Setting label orientation, margins c(bottom, left, top, right) & text size

par(las=1, mar=c(4, 4, 2, 4), cex=.7)

points(x, y1, pch=16, cex=2) # Try different cex value?

axis(1, at=seq(0, 16, 4)) # What is the first number standing for? The horizontal axis

mtext("Responses per Second", side=4, line=2, las=0, cex=0.8)
text(4, 5, "Bird 131")
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1), col="black", fg="black", col.axis="black")

# Histogram
# Random data
Y <- rnorm(50)
# Make sure no Y exceed [-3.5, 3.5]
Y[Y < -3.5 | Y > 3.5] <- NA # Selection/set range
x <- seq(-3.5, 3.5, .1)
dn <- dnorm(x)
par(mar=c(4.5, 4.1, 3.1, 0))
hist(Y, breaks=seq(-3.5, 3.5), ylim=c(0, 0.5), 
     col="gray80", freq=FALSE)

par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1))

# Barplot
par(mar=c(2, 3.1, 2, 2.1)) 
midpts <- barplot(VADeaths, 
                  col=gray(0.1 + seq(1, 9, 2)/11), 
                  names=rep("", 4))
mtext(sub(" ", "\n", colnames(VADeaths)),
      at=midpts, side=1, line=0.5, cex=0.5)
text(rep(midpts, each=5), apply(VADeaths, 2, cumsum) - VADeaths/2,
     VADeaths, 
     col=rep(c("white", "black"), times=3:2), 
     cex=0.8)
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1))  

# Boxplot
par(mar=c(3, 4.1, 2, 0))
boxplot(len ~ dose, data = ToothGrowth,
        boxwex = 0.25, at = 1:3 - 0.2,
        subset= supp == "VC", col="white",
        xlab="",
        ylab="tooth length", ylim=c(0,35))
mtext("Vitamin C dose (mg)", side=1, line=2.5, cex=0.8)
boxplot(len ~ dose, data = ToothGrowth, add = TRUE,
        boxwex = 0.25, at = 1:3 + 0.2,
        
        subset= supp == "OJ")
legend(1.5, 9, c("Ascorbic acid", "Orange juice"), 
       fill = c("white", "gray"), 
       bty="n")
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1))

# Persp
x <- seq(-10, 10, length= 30)
y <- x
f <- function(x,y) { r <- sqrt(x^2+y^2); 10 * sin(r)/r }
z <- outer(x, y, f)
z[is.na(z)] <- 1
# 0.5 to include z axis label
par(mar=c(0, 0.5, 0, 0), lwd=0.5)
persp(x, y, z, theta = 30, phi = 30, 
      expand = 0.5)
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1), lwd=1)

# Piechart
par(mar=c(0, 2, 1, 2), xpd=FALSE, cex=0.5)
pie.sales <- c(0.12, 0.3, 0.26, 0.16, 0.04, 0.12)
names(pie.sales) <- c("Blueberry", "Cherry",
                      "Apple", "Boston Cream", "Other", "Vanilla")
pie(pie.sales, col = gray(seq(0.3,1.0,length=6))) 









# Exercise: Can you generate these charts individually?  Try these functions using another dataset. Be sure to work on the layout and margins

library(readxl)

Warning: package 'readxl' was built under R version 4.3.3

# Set the path to your file
file_path1 <- "C:/Users/nabil/Downloads/HPI.xlsx"

# Read the Excel file
HPI <- read_excel(file_path1)

New names:
• `` -> `...4`



# Histogram of Life Expectancy
par(mfrow = c(1, 1))  # Set default plot layout
hist(HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, 
     main = "Distribution of Life Expectancy", 
     xlab = "Life Expectancy (years)", 
     col = "lightblue", 
     border = "black")









# Bar chart of average Life Expectancy by Continent
avg_life_exp <- tapply(HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, HPI$Continent, mean, na.rm=TRUE)
bar_colors <- "lightgreen"

# Create the bar plot
barplot(avg_life_exp, col = bar_colors, ylim = c(0, 90), 
        main = "Average Life Expectancy by Continent", 
        xlab = "Continent", ylab = "Average Life Expectancy (years)")

# Add axis and box around the plot
box()    # Draw a box around the plot

# Add a legend at the top-right corner (not cluttered)
legend("topright", legend = names(avg_life_exp), fill = bar_colors, cex = 0.8)









# Boxplot of Carbon Footprint by Continent
boxplot(HPI$`Carbon Footprint (tCO2e)` ~ HPI$Continent, 
        main = "Carbon Footprint by Continent", 
        xlab = "Continent", 
        ylab = "Carbon Footprint (tCO2e)", 
        col = "lightgreen")









# Pie chart for the number of countries by continent
continent_table <- table(HPI$Continent)
pie(continent_table, 
    col = rainbow(length(continent_table)))

# Add margin text for description
mtext("Pie Chart of Countries by Continent", side = 3, line = 2)









# Line chart of HPI Rank vs Life Expectancy
plot(HPI$`HPI rank`, HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, 
     type = "n",  # Create an empty plot first
     xlab = "HPI Rank", ylab = "Life Expectancy (years)")

# Add lines and points
lines(HPI$`HPI rank`, HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, col = "blue")
points(HPI$`HPI rank`, HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, pch = 19, col = "red")

# Add text labels to specific points
mtext("Line Chart of HPI Rank vs Life Expectancy", side = 3, line = 2)









# Prepare sorted values for x (life_exp) and y (gdp)
life_exp_sorted <- sort(unique(HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`))
gdp_sorted <- sort(unique(HPI$`GDP per capita ($)`))

# Create a grid of x (life_exp) and y (gdp)
life_exp_grid <- seq(min(life_exp_sorted), max(life_exp_sorted), length.out = 50)
gdp_grid <- seq(min(gdp_sorted), max(gdp_sorted), length.out = 50)

# Interpolate z (hpi) values into a matrix form that corresponds to the grid
# We will use a simple interpolation method here for the sake of the 3D plot
hpi_matrix <- outer(life_exp_grid, gdp_grid, FUN = function(x, y) {
  # Use a simple linear model or any function relating life expectancy and GDP to HPI
  # For simplicity, let's assume HPI increases with both life expectancy and GDP
  return((x / max(life_exp_grid)) * (y / max(gdp_grid)) * max(HPI$HPI, na.rm = TRUE))
})

# Create the 3D perspective plot
persp(life_exp_grid, gdp_grid, hpi_matrix, 
      theta = 30, phi = 20, 
      col = "lightblue", 
      xlab = "Life Expectancy (years)", 
      ylab = "GDP per Capita ($)", 
      zlab = "HPI",
      main = "3D Perspective of Life Expectancy, GDP, and HPI")

title: About
text:
I am Nabila Parijat. I am a third year PhD student in the Public and Nonprofit Management Program the University of Texas at Dallas (UTD). My research interests include program evaluation, performance measurement and immigration. Currently, I am studying the labor market effects of high-skilled immigration to the United States (US) through the H1B program, as well as how skilled immigration influences innovation. I am concurrently submitting and presenting research in conferences relating to the effectiveness of US-funded programs in food assistance and foreign aid.
Please view my Resume to know further about me. I am interested in research-related positions in academia, local and international nonprofits, as well as thinktanks.

Difference between downloading data from Google Trends and using gtrends to collect data
Downloading data from Google Trends requires us to click different download buttons that are present in the Google Trends website. This may seem like an easy task, but can get cumbersome. For example, if we are to download data from different countries across the world, we have to manually select different countries from a dropdown, and then download their data. With gtrends, this is completed with a single code. Therefore, this process is much less time consuming.

# Assignment 2

### Paul Murrell's R examples (selected)

plot(pressure, pch=16)  # You can change the pch according to your needs
text(150, 600, 
     "Pressure (mm Hg)\nversus\nTemperature (Celsius)")









#  Examples of standard high-level plots 

### Setting the parameter (3 rows by 2 cols)
par(mfrow=c(3, 2))

## Scatterplot

x <- c(0.5, 2, 4, 8, 12, 16)
y1 <- c(1, 1.3, 1.9, 3.4, 3.9, 4.8)
y2 <- c(4, .8, .5, .45, .4, .3)

## Setting label orientation, margins c(bottom, left, top, right) & text size

par(las=1, mar=c(4, 4, 2, 4), cex=.7) 
plot.new()
plot.window(range(x), c(0, 6))
lines(x, y1)
lines(x, y2)
points(x, y1, pch=16, cex=2) # Try different cex value?  
points(x, y2, pch=21, bg="red", cex=2)  # Different background color
par(col="gray50", fg="gray50", col.axis="gray50")
axis(1, at=seq(0, 16, 4)) # What is the first number standing for? The horizontal axis
axis(2, at=seq(0, 6, 2))
axis(4, at=seq(0, 6, 2))
box(bty="u")
mtext("Travel Time (s)", side=1, line=2, cex=0.8)
mtext("Responses per Travel", side=2, line=2, las=0, cex=0.8)
mtext("Responses per Second", side=4, line=2, las=0, cex=0.8)
text(4, 5, "Bird 131")
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1), col="black", fg="black", col.axis="black")

# Histogram
# Random data
Y <- rnorm(50)
# Make sure no Y exceed [-3.5, 3.5]
Y[Y < -3.5 | Y > 3.5] <- NA # Selection/set range
x <- seq(-3.5, 3.5, .1)
dn <- dnorm(x)
par(mar=c(4.5, 4.1, 3.1, 0))
hist(Y, breaks=seq(-3.5, 3.5), ylim=c(0, 0.5), 
     col="gray80", freq=FALSE)
lines(x, dnorm(x), lwd=2)
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1))

# Barplot
par(mar=c(2, 3.1, 2, 2.1)) 
midpts <- barplot(VADeaths, 
                  col=gray(0.1 + seq(1, 9, 2)/11), 
                  names=rep("", 4))
mtext(sub(" ", "\n", colnames(VADeaths)),
      at=midpts, side=1, line=0.5, cex=0.5)
text(rep(midpts, each=5), apply(VADeaths, 2, cumsum) - VADeaths/2,
     VADeaths, 
     col=rep(c("white", "black"), times=3:2), 
     cex=0.8)
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1))  

# Boxplot
par(mar=c(3, 4.1, 2, 0))
boxplot(len ~ dose, data = ToothGrowth,
        boxwex = 0.25, at = 1:3 - 0.2,
        subset= supp == "VC", col="white",
        xlab="",
        ylab="tooth length", ylim=c(0,35))
mtext("Vitamin C dose (mg)", side=1, line=2.5, cex=0.8)
boxplot(len ~ dose, data = ToothGrowth, add = TRUE,
        boxwex = 0.25, at = 1:3 + 0.2,
        
        subset= supp == "OJ")
legend(1.5, 9, c("Ascorbic acid", "Orange juice"), 
       fill = c("white", "gray"), 
       bty="n")
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1))

# Persp
x <- seq(-10, 10, length= 30)
y <- x
f <- function(x,y) { r <- sqrt(x^2+y^2); 10 * sin(r)/r }
z <- outer(x, y, f)
z[is.na(z)] <- 1
# 0.5 to include z axis label
par(mar=c(0, 0.5, 0, 0), lwd=0.5)
persp(x, y, z, theta = 30, phi = 30, 
      expand = 0.5)
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1), lwd=1)

# Piechart
par(mar=c(0, 2, 1, 2), xpd=FALSE, cex=0.5)
pie.sales <- c(0.12, 0.3, 0.26, 0.16, 0.04, 0.12)
names(pie.sales) <- c("Blueberry", "Cherry",
                      "Apple", "Boston Cream", "Other", "Vanilla")
pie(pie.sales, col = gray(seq(0.3,1.0,length=6))) 









# Exercise: Can you generate these charts individually?  Try these functions using another dataset. Be sure to work on the layout and margins

library(readxl)

Warning: package 'readxl' was built under R version 4.3.3

# Set the path to your file
file_path1 <- "C:/Users/nabil/Downloads/HPI.xlsx"

# Read the Excel file
HPI <- read_excel(file_path1)

New names:
• `` -> `...4`



# Histogram of Life Expectancy
par(mfrow = c(1, 1))  # Set default plot layout
hist(HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, 
     main = "Distribution of Life Expectancy", 
     xlab = "Life Expectancy (years)", 
     col = "lightblue", 
     border = "black")









# Bar chart of average Life Expectancy by Continent
avg_life_exp <- tapply(HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, HPI$Continent, mean, na.rm=TRUE)
bar_colors <- "lightgreen"

# Create the bar plot
barplot(avg_life_exp, col = bar_colors, ylim = c(0, 90), 
        main = "Average Life Expectancy by Continent", 
        xlab = "Continent", ylab = "Average Life Expectancy (years)")

# Add axis and box around the plot
box()    # Draw a box around the plot

# Add a legend at the top-right corner (not cluttered)
legend("topright", legend = names(avg_life_exp), fill = bar_colors, cex = 0.8)









# Boxplot of Carbon Footprint by Continent
boxplot(HPI$`Carbon Footprint (tCO2e)` ~ HPI$Continent, 
        main = "Carbon Footprint by Continent", 
        xlab = "Continent", 
        ylab = "Carbon Footprint (tCO2e)", 
        col = "lightgreen")









# Pie chart for the number of countries by continent
continent_table <- table(HPI$Continent)
pie(continent_table, 
    col = rainbow(length(continent_table)))

# Add margin text for description
mtext("Pie Chart of Countries by Continent", side = 3, line = 2)









# Line chart of HPI Rank vs Life Expectancy
plot(HPI$`HPI rank`, HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, 
     type = "n",  # Create an empty plot first
     xlab = "HPI Rank", ylab = "Life Expectancy (years)")

# Add lines and points
lines(HPI$`HPI rank`, HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, col = "blue")
points(HPI$`HPI rank`, HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, pch = 19, col = "red")

# Add text labels to specific points
mtext("Line Chart of HPI Rank vs Life Expectancy", side = 3, line = 2)









# Prepare sorted values for x (life_exp) and y (gdp)
life_exp_sorted <- sort(unique(HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`))
gdp_sorted <- sort(unique(HPI$`GDP per capita ($)`))

# Create a grid of x (life_exp) and y (gdp)
life_exp_grid <- seq(min(life_exp_sorted), max(life_exp_sorted), length.out = 50)
gdp_grid <- seq(min(gdp_sorted), max(gdp_sorted), length.out = 50)

# Interpolate z (hpi) values into a matrix form that corresponds to the grid
# We will use a simple interpolation method here for the sake of the 3D plot
hpi_matrix <- outer(life_exp_grid, gdp_grid, FUN = function(x, y) {
  # Use a simple linear model or any function relating life expectancy and GDP to HPI
  # For simplicity, let's assume HPI increases with both life expectancy and GDP
  return((x / max(life_exp_grid)) * (y / max(gdp_grid)) * max(HPI$HPI, na.rm = TRUE))
})

# Create the 3D perspective plot
persp(life_exp_grid, gdp_grid, hpi_matrix, 
      theta = 30, phi = 20, 
      col = "lightblue", 
      xlab = "Life Expectancy (years)", 
      ylab = "GDP per Capita ($)", 
      zlab = "HPI",
      main = "3D Perspective of Life Expectancy, GDP, and HPI")

title: Assignment 3

Y <- rnorm(50) # Generates 50 random values from a normal distribution (mean = 0, sd = 1)
Y[Y < -3.5 | Y > 3.5] <- NA # Selection/set range - makes sure no Y exceeds [-3.5, 3.5]
x <- seq(-3.5, 3.5, .1) # Creates a sequence of x values from -3.5 to 3.5 with step size of 0.1
dn <- dnorm(x) # Calculates the density of the normal distribution at each value of x. dnorm(x) gives the corresponding y-values for the normal distribution curve
par(mar=c(4.5, 4.1, 3.1, 0)) # 'mar' sets the margin sizes around the plot. mar = c(bottom, left, top, right) dimensions in lines of text. par() resets the default margins for future plots. Therefore, par() is the function used to set various graphical parameters for plots, while mar is a specific parameter within par() that adjusts the size of the margins around the plot. mar allows you to control the space around the plot.
hist(Y, breaks=seq(-3.5, 3.5), ylim=c(0, 0.5),
     col="gray80", freq=FALSE) # Create the histogram. breaks sets the bins for the histogram at intervals of 0.1 between -3.5 and 3.5. ylim sets the limits of the y-axis from 0 to 0.5. col sets the color of the histogram bars to light gray. 'freq=FALSE' means the histogram will display probabilities (density) instead of frequencies.
lines(x, dnorm(x), lwd=2) # 'lines(x, dnorm(x))' plots the normal curve using the x sequence and its corresponding density values. 'lwd=2' sets the line width of the curve to 2 (making it thicker). dnorm adds the normal distribution curve







par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1)) # Reset to default margin settings

## To analyze the hashtags, we create a subset DFM of hashtag tokens:

head(toptag, 10)

This identifies the top hashtags, such as #china, #biden, #xijinping. A high frequency of these tags indicates the most discussed topics surrounding the summit.

tag_fcm <- fcm(tag_dfm)
head(tag_fcm)

The FCM reveals which hashtags commonly appear together. #biden and #china have high co-occurrence, indicating that they are frequently discussed together.

textplot_network(topgat_fcm, min_freq = 50, edge_alpha = 0.8, edge_size = 1)








The network graph above shows the major hashtags surrounding the summit. The lines attached to the hashtags show which hashtags are connected.”#xi” and “#xijinping” are closely linked to “#China” and “#CCP”. “#UyghurGenocide”, “#Uyghurs”, and “#Taiwan” are primarily connected to “#China”. “#America” in linked to hashtags like “#Biden”, “#JoeBiden”, “#Americans”, and “#Coronavirus”. These connection indicate that discussions surrounding China are primarily related to the Uyghur and Taiwan issue, and discussions surrounding America are primarily related to US politics and the Coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic.

Difference between downloading data from Google Trends and using gtrends to collect data
Downloading data from Google Trends requires us to click different download buttons that are present in the Google Trends website. This may seem like an easy task, but can get cumbersome. For example, if we are to download data from different countries across the world, we have to manually select different countries from a dropdown, and then download their data. With gtrends, this is completed with a single code. Therefore, this process is much less time consuming.

# Directory to save the pdf's
save_dir <- "C://Users//nabil//Downloads"

# Function to download pdfs
download_govfiles_pdf <- function(url, id) {
  tryCatch({
    destfile <- paste0(save_dir, "govfiles_", id, ".pdf")
    download.file(url, destfile = destfile, mode = "wb") # Binary files
    Sys.sleep(runif(1, 1, 3))  # Important: random sleep between 1 and 3 seconds to avoid suspicion of "hacking" the server
    return(paste("Successfully downloaded:", url))
  },
  error = function(e) {
    return(paste("Failed to download:", url))

}

# Directory to save the pdf's
save_dir <- "C://Users//nabil//Downloads"

# Function to download pdfs
download_govfiles_pdf <- function(url, id) {
  tryCatch({
    destfile <- paste0(save_dir, "govfiles_", id, ".pdf")
    download.file(url, destfile = destfile, mode = "wb") # Binary files
    Sys.sleep(runif(1, 1, 3))  # Important: random sleep between 1 and 3 seconds to avoid suspicion of "hacking" the server
    return(paste("Successfully downloaded:", url))
  },
  error = function(e) {
    return(paste("Failed to download:", url))
  })
}

Examples of standard high-level plots

### Setting the parameter (3 rows by 2 cols)

par(mfrow=c(3, 2))

## Scatterplot

x <- c(0.5, 2, 4, 8, 12, 16)
y1 <- c(1, 1.3, 1.9, 3.4, 3.9, 4.8)

### Setting label orientation, margins c(bottom, left, top, right) & text size

par(las=1, mar=c(4, 4, 2, 4), cex=.7) 
plot.new()
plot.window(range(x), c(0, 6))
lines(x, y1)
lines(x, y2)
points(x, y1, pch=16, cex=2) # Try different cex value?  
points(x, y2, pch=21, bg="red", cex=2)  # Different background color
par(col="gray50", fg="gray50", col.axis="gray50")
axis(1, at=seq(0, 16, 4)) # What is the first number standing for? The horizontal axis
axis(2, at=seq(0, 6, 2))
axis(4, at=seq(0, 6, 2))
box(bty="u")
mtext("Travel Time (s)", side=1, line=2, cex=0.8)
mtext("Responses per Travel", side=2, line=2, las=0, cex=0.8)
mtext("Responses per Second", side=4, line=2, las=0, cex=0.8)
text(4, 5, "Bird 131")
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1), col="black", fg="black", col.axis="black")

## Histogram
### Random data
Y <- rnorm(50)
### Make sure no Y exceed [-3.5, 3.5]
Y[Y < -3.5 | Y > 3.5] <- NA # Selection/set range
x <- seq(-3.5, 3.5, .1)
dn <- dnorm(x)
par(mar=c(4.5, 4.1, 3.1, 0))
hist(Y, breaks=seq(-3.5, 3.5), ylim=c(0, 0.5), 
     col="gray80", freq=FALSE)
lines(x, dnorm(x), lwd=2)
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1))

## Barplot
par(mar=c(2, 3.1, 2, 2.1)) 
midpts <- barplot(VADeaths, 
                  col=gray(0.1 + seq(1, 9, 2)/11), 
                  names=rep("", 4))
mtext(sub(" ", "\n", colnames(VADeaths)),
      at=midpts, side=1, line=0.5, cex=0.5)
text(rep(midpts, each=5), apply(VADeaths, 2, cumsum) - VADeaths/2,
     VADeaths, 
     col=rep(c("white", "black"), times=3:2), 
     cex=0.8)
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1))  

## Boxplot
par(mar=c(3, 4.1, 2, 0))
boxplot(len ~ dose, data = ToothGrowth,
        boxwex = 0.25, at = 1:3 - 0.2,
        subset= supp == "VC", col="white",
        xlab="",
        ylab="tooth length", ylim=c(0,35))
mtext("Vitamin C dose (mg)", side=1, line=2.5, cex=0.8)
boxplot(len ~ dose, data = ToothGrowth, add = TRUE,
        boxwex = 0.25, at = 1:3 + 0.2,
        
        subset= supp == "OJ")
legend(1.5, 9, c("Ascorbic acid", "Orange juice"), 
       fill = c("white", "gray"), 
       bty="n")
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1))

## Persp
x <- seq(-10, 10, length= 30)
y <- x
f <- function(x,y) { r <- sqrt(x^2+y^2); 10 * sin(r)/r }
z <- outer(x, y, f)
z[is.na(z)] <- 1
# 0.5 to include z axis label
par(mar=c(0, 0.5, 0, 0), lwd=0.5)
persp(x, y, z, theta = 30, phi = 30, 
      expand = 0.5)
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1), lwd=1)

## Piechart
par(mar=c(0, 2, 1, 2), xpd=FALSE, cex=0.5)

pie(pie.sales, col = gray(seq(0.3,1.0,length=6)))

Exercise: Can you generate these charts individually? Try these functions using another dataset. Be sure to work on the layout and margins

library(readxl)

Warning: package 'readxl' was built under R version 4.3.3

### Set the path to your file
file_path1 <- "C:/Users/nabil/Downloads/HPI.xlsx"

### Read the Excel file
HPI <- read_excel(file_path1)

New names:
• `` -> `...4`



Histogram of Life Expectancy

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))  # Set default plot layout
hist(HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, 
     main = "Distribution of Life Expectancy", 
     xlab = "Life Expectancy (years)", 
     col = "lightblue", 
     border = "black")










Bar chart of average Life Expectancy by Continent

avg_life_exp <- tapply(HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, HPI$Continent, mean, na.rm=TRUE)
bar_colors <- "lightgreen"

## Create the bar plot
barplot(avg_life_exp, col = bar_colors, ylim = c(0, 90), 
        main = "Average Life Expectancy by Continent", 
        xlab = "Continent", ylab = "Average Life Expectancy (years)")

### Add axis and box around the plot
box()    # Draw a box around the plot

### Add a legend at the top-right corner (not cluttered)
legend("topright", legend = names(avg_life_exp), fill = bar_colors, cex = 0.8)










Boxplot of Carbon Footprint by Continent

boxplot(HPI$`Carbon Footprint (tCO2e)` ~ HPI$Continent, 
        main = "Carbon Footprint by Continent", 
        xlab = "Continent", 
        ylab = "Carbon Footprint (tCO2e)", 
        col = "lightgreen")










Pie chart for the number of countries by continent

continent_table <- table(HPI$Continent)
pie(continent_table, 
    col = rainbow(length(continent_table)))

#### Add margin text for description
mtext("Pie Chart of Countries by Continent", side = 3, line = 2)










Line chart of HPI Rank vs Life Expectancy

plot(HPI$`HPI rank`, HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, 
     type = "n",  # Create an empty plot first
     xlab = "HPI Rank", ylab = "Life Expectancy (years)")

#### Add lines and points
lines(HPI$`HPI rank`, HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, col = "blue")
points(HPI$`HPI rank`, HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`, pch = 19, col = "red")

#### Add text labels to specific points
mtext("Line Chart of HPI Rank vs Life Expectancy", side = 3, line = 2)










Prepare sorted values for x (life_exp) and y (gdp)

life_exp_sorted <- sort(unique(HPI$`Life Expectancy (years)`))
gdp_sorted <- sort(unique(HPI$`GDP per capita ($)`))

#### Create a grid of x (life_exp) and y (gdp)
life_exp_grid <- seq(min(life_exp_sorted), max(life_exp_sorted), length.out = 50)
gdp_grid <- seq(min(gdp_sorted), max(gdp_sorted), length.out = 50)

### Interpolate z (hpi) values into a matrix form that corresponds to the grid. We will use a simple interpolation method here for the sake of the 3D plot
hpi_matrix <- outer(life_exp_grid, gdp_grid, FUN = function(x, y) {
  #### Use a simple linear model or any function relating life expectancy and GDP to HPI
  #### For simplicity, let's assume HPI increases with both life expectancy and GDP
  return((x / max(life_exp_grid)) * (y / max(gdp_grid)) * max(HPI$HPI, na.rm = TRUE))
})

## Create the 3D perspective plot
persp(life_exp_grid, gdp_grid, hpi_matrix, 
      theta = 30, phi = 20, 
      col = "lightblue", 
      xlab = "Life Expectancy (years)", 
      ylab = "GDP per Capita ($)", 
      zlab = "HPI",
      main = "3D Perspective of Life Expectancy, GDP, and HPI")

The differences in these file formats are that, PDF files tend to look larger, more legible and professional. But PDFs are not image-type files by default. Pdfs can also be fillable, that is, they can operate as alsmost a word document with a more professional aesthetic and a format that doesn’t change.JPGs are image-type formats that are smaller in size than PDFs and have defined borders. They are often used for photos. SVGs are also image-type files, and their small file sizes make them useful for mobile viewing.

Y <- rnorm(50) # Generates 50 random values from a normal distribution (mean = 0, sd = 1)
Y[Y < -3.5 | Y > 3.5] <- NA # Selection/set range - makes sure no Y exceeds [-3.5, 3.5]
x <- seq(-3.5, 3.5, .1) # Creates a sequence of x values from -3.5 to 3.5 with step size of 0.1
dn <- dnorm(x) # Calculates the density of the normal distribution at each value of x. dnorm(x) gives the corresponding y-values for the normal distribution curve
par(mar=c(4.5, 4.1, 3.1, 0)) # 'mar' sets the margin sizes around the plot. mar = c(bottom, left, top, right) dimensions in lines of text. par() resets the default margins for future plots. Therefore, par() is the function used to set various graphical parameters for plots, while mar is a specific parameter within par() that adjusts the size of the margins around the plot. mar allows you to control the space around the plot.
hist(Y, breaks=seq(-3.5, 3.5), ylim=c(0, 0.5),
     col="gray80", freq=FALSE) # Create the histogram. breaks sets the bins for the histogram at intervals of 0.1 between -3.5 and 3.5. ylim sets the limits of the y-axis from 0 to 0.5. col sets the color of the histogram bars to light gray. 'freq=FALSE' means the histogram will display probabilities (density) instead of frequencies.
lines(x, dnorm(x), lwd=2) # 'lines(x, dnorm(x))' plots the normal curve using the x sequence and its corresponding density values. 'lwd=2' sets the line width of the curve to 2 (making it thicker). dnorm adds the normal distribution curve







par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1)) # Reset to default margin settings

2 (a) Comparison of the Regression Models
The four regression models are extremely similar. All four models have almost identical coefficients for both the intercept and slope. For all four models, the intercept is approximately 3 (ranging from 3.0001 to 3.0025). The slope for all four models is approximately 0.5, meaning that for each unit increase in x, y is expected to increase by 0.5 units in each dataset. The p-values for the intercept and slope are very low (p<0.05), indicating that both the intercept and the slope are statistically significant in each case. All models have an R-squared of around 0.666, meaning that about 66.6% of the variation in y is explained by x in each dataset.

angle=22.5

status=data.frame(x=numeric(0), y=numeric(0), alfa=numeric(0))
points=data.frame(x1 = 0, y1 = 0, x2 = NA, y2 = NA, alfa=90, depth=1)

### Generating data

for (action in actions)
{
  if (action=="F")
  {
    x=points[1, "x1"]+cos(points[1, "alfa"]*(pi/180))
    y=points[1, "y1"]+sin(points[1, "alfa"]*(pi/180))
    points[1,"x2"]=x
    points[1,"y2"]=y
    data.frame(x1 = x, y1 = y, x2 = NA, y2 = NA,
               alfa=points[1, "alfa"],
               depth=points[1,"depth"]) %>% rbind(points)->points
  }
  if (action %in% c("+", "-")){
    alfa=points[1, "alfa"]
    points[1, "alfa"]=eval(parse(text=paste0("alfa",action, angle)))
  }
  if(action=="["){
    data.frame(x=points[1, "x1"], y=points[1, "y1"], alfa=points[1, "alfa"]) %>%
      rbind(status) -> status
    points[1, "depth"]=points[1, "depth"]+1
  }

  if(action=="]"){
    depth=points[1, "depth"]
    points[-1,]->points
    data.frame(x1=status[1, "x"], y1=status[1, "y"], x2=NA, y2=NA,
               alfa=status[1, "alfa"],
               depth=depth-1) %>%
      rbind(points) -> points
    status[-1,]->status
  }
}
